So many features, so little time.  Now power and automation make Word 6.0
.  .  .

You threw away your typewriter back when Bill Gates was merely a
millionaire and the 286 was the hottest CPU on the street.  But the ghost
of that clattering mechanical beast lives on in the word processor you
use every day.

Most of us still treat our word processors like glorified typewriters.
We pound text onto the screen as fast as our fingers can dance across the
keys.  Yes, we use the backspace key, and occasionally we cut a sentence
from here and paste it there.  If there's time, we add a dash of boldface
or italic for emphasis.  An adventurous few of us actually run a
spell-checker before we hit the Print icon.  But most of us never use
more than a fraction of the immense potential in today's leading word
processors because that power is trapped behind intimidating, unfamiliar
interfaces.

Listen carefully: Your word processor is not a typewriter.  Used fully,
it's an intelligent collaborator in putting ideas on paper.  Now there's
finally a word processor that makes it easy, almost inevitable, to access
that power.

Thankfully, the new Word for Windows is not packed with new features.
Instead, it's filled to the brim with usability improvements and
one-button shortcuts to powerful capabilities that have been part of the
program for years.  Microsoft skipped from Version 2.0 straight to 6.0
with this release of Word, ostensibly to keep pace with the DOS and
Macintosh versions of Word. But the big leap in numbering is appropriate
for another reason: This Word is light-years ahead of any Word you've
ever seen.  And until the competition catches up--next month or next
year--it's arguably the most usable word processor you can buy.

SIMPLY POWERFUL

What's new in Word 6.0 for Windows? Countless little improvements and a
handful of really big ones.  The biggest new feature is its ability to
power through complicated tasks with push-button simplicity.  If you can
do it with a word processor, this word processor can do it automatically,
thanks to AutoFormat, AutoCorrect, and a handful of other Auto features.

Then there's the small stuff.  The longer you stare at the Word 6.0
screen, the more new elements you'll see: multiple toolbars with colorful
icons, a redesigned ruler and status bar, completely revamped dialog
boxes, and (at long last) a multiple document interface (MDI) that lets
you reduce each open window to an icon.  Virtually every dialog box and
function has been lifted out, simplified, refined, and reinstalled to
make the word processor work better as a whole.  Word is the last major
Microsoft application to get its own collection of Wizards (interactive
online help assistants).

And Word is among the first applications to support OLE 2.0, Microsoft's
new object linking and embedding standard that lets you combine multiple
data types in a single document.  (See "Share Data Seamlessly with OLE
2.0" on page 328.)

Is there a single "killer feature" in Microsoft Word 6.0 for Windows? No,
although the one-button AutoFormat capability comes close.  But taken as
a whole, the wide-ranging collection of small, pleasing interface
enhancements adds up to a big productivity boost.  You'll find yourself
experimenting with powerful features that you never realized were there
because now they're a snap to use.

With this release, Word joins an elite group of applications, like
Microsoft Excel and Lotus Freelance Graphics for Windows, that gauge your
work activities and try to anticipate what you'll do next--or, better
yet, five minutes from now.  It's a sensible strategy, grounded in the
realization that most of us perform the same monotonous tasks over and
over again.  And when you see how the new Word streamlines everyday word
processing, you'll wonder why all software doesn't work like this.

The Elements of Style

The idea of playing Pygmalion with a plain-Jane document is hardly new.
Excel for Windows and Borland's Quattro Pro for Windows have been
sprucing up spreadsheets for more than a year with AutoFormat and
SpeedFormat, respectively.  But Word is the first word processor that
does one-button, on-the-fly make-overs.

Here's what happens when you press the AutoFormat button: First, Word
intelligently parses the text into headings, subheadings, body text;
notes spacing, fonts, bullets, and so on; and creates style tags.  Then
Word lets you review its changes.  Finally, it pops up a dialog box that
lets you approve the changes or head straight to a gallery of predefined
style sheets. Pick the look you want, and Word applies it to your
document.  The result is a document that looks a whole lot better than
when you started.

But there's an additional, less obvious benefit to AutoFormat.  Because
all the formatting changes are tied to style tags, you can selectively
accept, reject, or edit the changes to the document.  Even better, you
can change a document's entire look by choosing another style-sheet
template from the Style Gallery--including fax cover sheets, letters,
resumes, or templates you create yourself.

Style Gallery offers three ways to see style sheets in its large,
scrollable preview window: using the actual text in your document, using
a complex example document, or using an itemized list of the selected
template's style names with formatted sample text.  Once you customize a
template, you'll never again spend hours clicking away at the Format menu
to reinvent that desired appearance.

Anyone intimidated by Word 2.0's rigid approach to styles will want to
check out the new Style Manager.  Like Lotus's Ami Pro 3.0, Word 6.0
previews the style for you, but it goes Ami Pro one step better by using
live copy.  Like WordPerfect, Word 6.0 now supports character and
paragraph styles.  The Style dialog box itself is a superbly organized
control panel; even if you never grasp the concept of styles, you'll
likely find yourself using them.

Other formatting enhancements have been lifted from a variety of sources.
 Ami Pro's Fast Format shows up in Word 6.0 as the Format Painter.  Both
programs let you copy formatting from one piece of text and "paint" that
formatting on to other text throughout a document.  Word's new Table
AutoFormat, borrowed from Excel 4.0, does for Word tables what AutoFormat
does for text, complete with colorful headings.

Border and shading options are dramatically richer.  Bullets are more
accessible.  And Word finally does numbered lists right: When you insert
a new item into a list, Word automatically renumbers succeeding items.

Visible Improvements

As any cosmetic surgeon worth his Mercedes will tell you, the best
face-lift looks completely natural.  That's the case with the artfully
reconstructed Word 6.0 interface, where none of the subtle improvements
is likely to jump out at you immediately.  The ruler is redesigned, with
a 3-D look that also extends to the new tabbed dialog boxes--a look, not
coincidentally, that's exactly like Excel's.  Every dialog box includes a
Help button for context-sensitive reference.

Toolbars take up more screen real estate than anything else in the new
Word, and they're worth it.  Where Word 2.0 included a single toolbar
plus a formatting Ribbon, Word 6.0 ships with 13 predefined toolbars.  In
addition to the standard toolbar, there are toolbars for formatting,
borders, database access, drawing, and forms, plus one set of toolbars
that mirrors the Word 2.0 for Windows toolbar.  Five other toolbars pop
up automatically in conjunction with specific operations, such as Mail
Merge.

Microsoft's designers obviously studied Lotus's SmartIcons in detail,
borrowing liberally and improving the interface occasionally.  As with
SmartIcons, you can boost the size of the tiny default icons with one
mouse click.  The ToolTips feature automatically pops up a bright yellow
label for any toolbar button when you leave the mouse pointer poised over
the icon for more than a second.

Out of the box, Word includes more than 200 color icons arranged in 11
fixed palettes that correspond to top-level menu and dialog functions.
And Word has finally caught up with arch rivals WordPerfect and Ami Pro
in the drag-and-drop derby: To modify a toolbar, you drag an icon from
the Customize dialog box and drop it on any open toolbar.  To delete an
icon, just drag it off.

As with Ami Pro's SmartIcons and WordPerfect's Button Bars, you can snap
Word toolbars along any edge of the screen or leave them floating.  To
open or close toolbars, you click the right-mouse button anywhere in any
toolbar.  You get a pop-up menu that lets you click on available toolbar
names to toggle them open or closed.

Applied Intelligence

When the multimedia edition of Word 6.0 hits the streets, listen for the
sound of footsteps coming out of your PC's speaker.  That will be Word
following a half-step behind you, cleaning up typos, misspellings, and
capitalization errors on the fly.  This occasionally unnerving feature is
called AutoCorrect, and it relies on algorithms and an editable
translation table to automatically clean up your writing.  The default
table includes a handful of ubiquitous misspellings (recieve instead of
receive) and transpositions (teh instead of the), but you can also use it
to expand abbreviations into common phrases.

AutoCorrect swings into action every time you hit the space bar (or a
period or other punctuation) after amisspelled word.  You can make the
feature act as a watchdog and a multilingual assistant by defining
AutoCorrect entries that patch in the correct spelling of words that use
special characters like accents and umlauts.  Check the proper boxes on
the Options dialog box, and AutoCorrect also replaces straight quotes for
smart quotes.  And if the whole notion of AutoCorrect gives you the
heebie-jeebies, you can turn it off completely.

The Word 6.0 development team lavished attention on one of the program's
tiniest features--text selection.  The result is a surprising increase in
efficiency.  By default, Word assumes that when you swipe the mouse
pointer over a word or choose a formatting option that you want to select
the entire word.  The result? You can click the mouse with reckless
imprecision and trust that you'll select or reformat the text you
intended.  You can disable this feature--but you won't want to.

Word 6.0 refines drag-and-drop editing by automatically ensuring that the
appropriate number of spaces are selected and inserted every time you
drag and drop, ensuring that all text in both the old and new locations
fits correctly.  And you can finally drag text from one open document and
drop it into another.

Word Processing made Easier

You'll quickly run out of fingers and thumbs if you try to tally up the
improvements in the new Word.  How about 100 levels of Undo and Redo? Or
fast background printing that keeps pace with Ami Pro? Fully editable
Print Preview with a thumbnail view? The ability to send documents via
e-mail, complete with routing slips and revision marks or document
comparisons? Database links via Microsoft Access? Shortcut menus
accessible with a click of the right-mouse button?

One new feature is aimed squarely at overcoming a common objection of
WordPerfect users: Click on the Help icon, then point to a block of text,
and Word pops up a box of formatting information.

Need help? Word has plenty of options.  In addition to the usual
context-sensitive help, dozens of animated demos walk you through common
business tasks.

How To help (resembling the Cue Cards found in other Microsoft
applications) remains visible while you work with a multistep feature.
And Word's Wizards automate the creation of complex documents, such as
agendas and calendars.

Merging styles and macros into other documents, which used to have an
Olympian degree of difficulty, is now kids' stuff, thanks to the all-new
Organizer.  It lets you open two template files, including Word's default
template, NORMAL.DOT, to copy, delete, or rename styles, macros,
toolbars, and AutoText (called Glossary in previous versions) items
between them.  For many Word experts, it's an answer to their prayers.

The Final Word

So, what's not to like about Word 6.0? Not much.  We've assembled a short
wish list (see "In Search of Perfection" on page 329), but we had to
stretch to do it.  If you're already a Word user, your decision is easy:
Upgrade today.  If you're looking for your first Windows word processor,
you can't go wrong by choosing the new Word, especially with its
unbeatable WordPerfect help and file-translation capabilities.  The
competition--WordPerfect for Windows and Ami Pro--aren't standing still.
But at least for now, this is the best Windows word processor around.

