Share Data Seamlessly with OLE 2.0

It's a snap to transfer and edit data among multiple apps.

With object linking and embedding (OLE) 2.0, combining data from multiple
sources is a simple drag-and-drop operation.

Its predecessor, OLE 1.0, forced you to work with the electronic
equivalent of scissors and paste; to edit an embedded object (a picture
in a text document, for example) you double-clicked on the object and
switched away from your original document (the OLE container).  OLE 2.0
lets you edit an embedded object in place--without visibly launching the
object's original application or opening a separate window.

In addition, with OLE 2.0 you can drag data from one application and drop
it into another to create an embedded or linked object.  During the
process, the container application's interface changes to reflect the
unique aspects of the object's native application.

The Automation functions of OLE 2.0 let programmers define a set of
operations in one application and make them available to other
applications.  For example, a word processor might beef up its table
functions by linking directly to spreadsheet formulas.

Microsoft is shipping Word 6.0, Excel 5.0, Publisher 2.0, and Visual
Basic 3.0 with full OLE 2.0 support.  Look for support of the spec in
other coming Microsoft applications.  More than 30 developers are working
on and have announced plans to support OLE 2.0 applications, including
Calera, Corel, Lotus Development, Macromedia, and WordPerfect.

