In Search of Perfection

Refined? You bet.  But what improvements does this terrific app still
need?

Is Word 6.0 for Windows the best word processor ever? Maybe.  We'll
reserve final judgment until next month, when we see what WordPerfect
does with its Version 6.0 for Windows upgrade.  In the meantime, though,
we've found eight areas where Word is less than perfect, especially when
compared with the latest versions of WordPerfect for Windows and Ami
Pro--or, for that matter, any state-of-the-art Windows software package.

1.  Built-in file management.  The most effective way to manage files is
to do so while you're working with them.  WordPerfect recognized this
long ago, and Microsoft should look at how easy WordPerfect makes it to
view, find, move, and delete files.  And the WordPerfect button that lets
you create a directory from inside the File Save dialog box is a
masterstroke that should be part of every Windows application, not just
Word.

2.  QuickFinder.  WordPerfect hit the word processing equivalent of a
home run when it built a fully indexed text search engine into its
flagship program.  Word (and Ami Pro) should do likewise.

3.  File Open box.  Click on File Open, and Word presents a list of every
file with the .DOC extension.  If your file-naming habits are more
creative, you'll need to jump through an extra mouse hoop every time.  Oh
well, at least Word, unlike Ami Pro, allows you to use alternate
extensions.

4.  Wizards.  It should be easy to build your own or customize existing
Wizards.  Why doesn't Microsoft offer a Wizard's magic sack?

5.  Right-mouse support.  WordPerfect and Ami Pro make extensive use of
the right mouse button.  With Version 6.0, Word barely scratches the
surface.  Adding more context-sensitive menus would be a big usability
improvement.

6.  User-configurable defaults.  It's easy to change settings in many
dialog boxes, such as Bullets and Numbering, but you can't save those
settings as new defaults.  Users don't want to go through this tedious
process every time they build a simple list.

7.  Icon-creation tools.  You'll want better ways to import and store
icons for Word 6.0 toolbars.  You can only save edited icons on a toolbar
(not individually), and Word's fixed palette of 37 unassigned icons
doesn't provide enough variety to cover most icon needs.  Word 6.0 lacks
the abilities to cut and paste icons from other icon libraries and to
capture icons from the screen.

8.  Screen-managing quick buttons.  Application toolbars need a button
that lets you close them to gain document space with a single click.  The
Standard toolbar should provide buttons that toggle the Ruler and Status
Bar on and off to control screen real estate.  And we hate scrolling:
Vertical scroll bars should have inset buttons that let you click once to
jump directly to the beginning or end of a document, mirroring the
keyboard's Ctrl- Home and Ctrl-End functions.

And that's it.  In virtually every detail, Word for Windows 6.0 has
redefined the target for usability.  Will WordPerfect and Lotus stand
still? Not hardly.  WordPerfect 6.0 for Windows (there's that number
again!) should hit the streets within weeks after Word appears.  And the
development team at Lotus will be taking a long look at both its rivals
to see how it can jump ahead in the game of word processing leapfrog.

For now, though, Word owns the high ground.

