Word 2.0 vs.  Word 6.0: There's No Contest

You'll find enhancements lurking in every dialog box.

Take the plunge into Word 6.0 for Windows and you'll feel like you're in
a different world, especially when you compare it to Word 2.0 for
Windows.  Virtually nothing remains the same.

When you look at the dialog boxes in Word 6.0 you'll find that features
are better organized, more accessible, and as a result, easier to use.
Tabbed dialog boxes let you see and access options with just the click of
a mouse.  And there are tunnels between dialog boxes that help you avoid
dead ends.  For example, you can access the Replace feature from the Edit
menu and the Find dialog box.  Notice also the Help button on every
dialog box, which provides context-sensitive assistance in times of
trouble.

While Word 2.0 did provide some visual hints to determine the look of
your document, it was nothing like Word 6.0, which uses live text to
preview elements whenever possible.  There are also visual presets, which
show the most commonly used predefined options.  These presets offer you
choices when you need them rather than expecting you to define elements
each time you use them.

A good example of visual presets is found in the Columns dialog box,
which predefines the five most common column settings from which you can
choose.  There are no more surprises in Word 6.0--you'll know what your
document will look like before it's even finished.

The new Zoom dialog box offers a visual representation of your text to
help you decide what exact screen-magnification size is best for your
needs.  The controls are nearly the same, but the effect is
different--and better.

The Columns dialog box is a perfect example of how suggested presets and
a preview make it easy to create and adjust columns.  Word 2.0's Columns
dialog box is plain by comparison, and was always difficult to use.

Word 6.0's tabbed-dialog Options screen offers easy access to your
configuration areas.  While Word 2.0's Options menu was colorful, you
couldn't access the vast number of options settings all on one screen.

Enhanced and nearly perfect, Word 6.0's Open dialog box adds the welcome
ability to open multiple documents simultaneously.  What more could you
want? Make it possible to set "All Files (*.*)" as a permanent default.
